    {
      "id": "5bed7d96_97336b38",
      "file_path": "mso-api-handlers/mso-api-handler-infra/src/main/java/org/onap/so/apihandlerinfra/MsoRequest.java",
      "patchset_number": 6,
      "line": 227,
      "message": "If you want to get value from map by key, there is no point to use stream to search value by key in the map. Another thing is that I would check if this value is not null. I would write:\n\n Optional.ofNullable(queryParams.get(FILTER_KEY)).ifPresent(list -> list.forEach((value ->\n                addValueToOrchestrationFilterParamsMap(orchestrationFilterParams, value))));",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2789,
        "name": "Lukasz Muszkieta",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "lukasz.muszkieta@nokia.com",
        "username": "lukaszM"
      },
      "updated": "2020-02-07 14:00:38.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "987a3fe0_848d3384",
      "file_path": "mso-api-handlers/mso-api-handler-infra/src/main/java/org/onap/so/apihandlerinfra/MsoRequest.java",
      "patchset_number": 6,
      "line": 235,
      "message": "I have a following problem with this logic:\nThis logic takes string for example;\n\"aaa:bbb:ccc\", and first element \"aaa\" is a key, and the rest of strings is put as list value. That is ok. \n\nBut this logic also allows two cases which I do not like:\n1. Put null key and empty list to the map if parameter value is empty\n2. Put the key and empty list to the map if the parameter value is like \"aaa:\"\n\nI think we should check first, if stringTokenizer.countTokens()==2, the we have a guarantee that if we put entry to the map, the key is not null and the list of strings will not be empty.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2789,
        "name": "Lukasz Muszkieta",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "lukasz.muszkieta@nokia.com",
        "username": "lukaszM"
      },
      "updated": "2020-02-07 14:00:38.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
